article.headline: Duke 119, Stephen F. Austin 53
article.story:
DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Duke has a post presence to go along with
its strong outside game built around All-American guard Alana
Beard.

Mistie Bass, a 6-foot-3 center, scored a career-high 21 points
on 9-for-10 shooting and added a career-best three blocks in 27
minutes, leading No. 4 Duke to a 119-53 victory over Stephen F.
Austin in the Duke Women's Basketball Classic.

"Mistie Bass gives Duke a real threat in the post," Stephen F.
Austin coach Lee Ann Riley said.

Duke (3-1) pounded the ball inside for its best shooting game
ever, making a team-record 68 percent (46-for-68).

The Blue Devils also outrebounded the LadyJacks 36-14, and
outscored Stephen F. Austin 70-20 in the paint.

"We knew they wanted to go inside," Riley said. "We couldn't
stop them. They just played with a lot of heart and we didn't."

Iciss Tillis led Duke with had 23 points and eight rebounds, and
Beard added 20 points as seven Blue Devils scored in double
figures.

Jessica Foley added 14, Monique Currie 12, Lindsay Harding 11
and Vicki Krapohl 10 for Duke.

"That showed off our balance," Duke coach Gail Goestenkors
said. "Everybody knows we've been emphasizing getting the ball
into our post players, and we did a good job doing that."

Duke jumped out to an 11-0 lead before the LadyJacks tied the
game at 18. Stephen F. Austin trailed 39-30 before Duke used a 33-3
run to put the game out of reach.

"We didn't play well at either end of the floor for a while,"
Goestenkors said. "We came out and played much better basketball
in the second half."

Duke shot 27-for-38 from the field in the second half (71.1
percent).

Reserve Latoya Mills led the LadyJacks with 12 points.

No. 25 Auburn (4-1) defeated Creighton 79-72 in Saturday's first
game, and will face Duke in the Classic final Sunday.
